headline: CNN News Central
subHeadline: End Of Interview With Rep. Mike Quigley (D-IL); Soon: Harris Speaks At First Presidential Rally In Milwaukee; Speaker Johnson: Election Should Not Be About Race Or Gender; Harris Holds First Presidential Rally. Aired 2:30-3p ET

utterances.speaker: BRIANNA KEILAR, CNN HOST
utterances.sentences: We heard Congressman Tim Burchett calling Vice President Harris a DEI hire, which has kind of become this almost like a like a veiled slur, I think.Because we see people using it when it just it doesn't even make sense of people who weren't hired, but maybe who are elected. And what we see is this tends to be something that has only said about people of color or people who are not men. I wonder what the effect is in your mind of some Republicans talking like that. But with also a nod to the fact that there are people within your own party who, while they think that Harris' background should be a benefit to her, the perspective that she brings and the representation that she brings, they also worry that some voters might not see it that way. What do you say?

utterances.speaker: QUIGLEY
utterances.sentences: Look, it's -- I believe it's intended as a slur. I think you're just going to -- just starting to see the beginnings of that. But I think the American people will see through that and unite against that sort of thing.And again, obviously, she's not a hire. She's elected by the people in the United States of America. And it's not the DEI labor -- label or past history that they're worried about with her. It's the fact that she was a prosecutor and their candidate is a convicted felon. This is a rich diverse country. We'd like to think of that as a strength, not a weakness. And why not be represented by someone who represents so much of that fabric that we treasure?

utterances.speaker: KEILAR
utterances.sentences: But what do you think about some of the energy from younger voters for Kamala Harris? I imagine you've had to learn what "Brat" is here in the last day or so.I mean, what are -- what are you making of this whole new world that I think the non-Gen-Z-ers are discovering.

utterances.speaker: QUIGLEY
utterances.sentences: Well, first, you touched on a good point. It is a whole new world. Because, you know, one of the reasons I was concerned before President Biden made his choice, was I was concerned about where young people were going to go in this upcoming election.I was concerned that they were to be apathetic or, you know, stay -- stay out of this entirely. I now no longer have those concerns of part of that base that's been revived is a very a young person's campaign. And I'm with them. Just watch. If the first 24 hours was this dynamic, now watch for the next 24 days. It's going to be fun to watch.

utterances.speaker: KEILAR
utterances.sentences: Do you worry it could fizzle?

utterances.speaker: QUIGLEY
utterances.sentences: No. Look, there's an adrenaline that comes with this and a momentum. And, again, that's exactly why -- one of the key reasons that President Biden stepped aside.There's a momentum in politics just like there is in sports. And that you have to make sometimes a change during that time to change the momentum. I think he see the field tilted the wrong way for the Republicans. That's what's concerning them. And I think that's why they're being so aggressive against her.

utterances.speaker: KEILAR
utterances.sentences: Congressman Mike Quigley, great to have you on. Thanks for being with us.

utterances.speaker: QUIGLEY
utterances.sentences: Thank you. Take care.

utterances.speaker: JESSICA DEAN, CNN HOST
utterances.sentences: And I want to get to CNN's Annie Grayer, who is live on Capitol Hill to talk more about these attacks on Vice President Harris.Annie, Mike Johnson is warning Republicans against attacking her on race and gender. What more are you learning about this?

utterances.speaker: GRAYER
utterances.sentences: to -- to concerns. So, we'll --(CROSSTALK)

utterances.speaker: GRAYER
utterances.sentences: So we're going to see how this --(CROSSTALK)

utterances.speaker: DEAN
utterances.sentences: Annie, I'm so sorry to interrupt you.Let's listen in on Vice President Kamala Harris. (CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: KAMALA HARRIS, VICE PRESIDENT OF THE UNITED STATES
utterances.sentences: Thank you.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: Thank you.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: Thank you.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: Thank you. Thank you, everyone.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: Thank you. Thank you.Good afternoon, Wisconsin. (CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: Good afternoon, everyone. Thank you. It is good to be back. Thank you all very much.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: Can we please hear it for Leah and her extraordinary story and leadership?(CHEERING) (APPLAUSE)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: And i do believe our teachers do God's work. They teach other people's children and God knows we don't pay them enough.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: Let's thank them.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: And it is so good to be here and be back with so many extraordinary leaders, including my friend, the great governor of Wisconsin, Tony Evers.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: My dear friend, Senator Tammy Baldwin.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: You know, I had the privilege of serving with Tammy when I was in the United States Senate. And she has always fighting for the people of this state.And I know that the folks that are here are going to make sure you return her to Washington, D.C. in November. (CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: Yes, we are going to elect her back to Washington, D.C.It is so good to be here also with Lieutenant Governor Sara Rodriguez. (CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: Attorney General Josh Kaul (ph).(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: Wisconsin's secretary of state, Sarah Godlewski.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: County executive, David Crowley.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: Mayor Cavalier Johnson.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: And the great state party chair, Ben Wikler.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: So I have worked with Ben.You and I've been working together for years. And I can attest he knows how to build the infrastructure that delivers wins up and down the ballot. Thank you, Ben. (CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: So it is good to be back in Wisconsin. And it is great to be in Milwaukee.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: As many of you know, our state campaign headquarters are in this city.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: And there is a reason for that. The path to the White House goes through Wisconsin.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: Yes, it does. And to win in Wisconsin, we are counting on you right here in Milwaukee.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: And you helped us win in 2020. And in 2024, we will win again.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: Yes, we will.So, Milwaukee, I want to start by saying a few words, and I could really speak at length, but a few words about our incredible President Joe Biden. (CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: It has truly been one of the greatest honors of my life to serve as vice president to our president, Joe Biden.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: Joe's legacy of accomplishment over his entire career and over the past 3.5 years is unmatched in modern history. In one term, think about it, in one term as president, he has already surpassed the legacy of most presidents who served two terms in office.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: And I know we are all deeply, deeply grateful for his continuing service to our nation.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: So, Wisconsin, I am told, as of this morning, that we have earned the support of enough delegates to secure the Democratic nomination.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: I am so very honored. And I pledge to you, I will spend the coming weeks continuing to unite our party so that we are ready to win in November.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: So, friends, we have 105 days until Election Day. And in that time, we've got some work to do. But we're not afraid of hard work. We like hard work, don't we?(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: And we will win this election.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: Yes, we will.So, as Leah told you before, I was elected vice president. Before I was a United States Senator, I was elected attorney general of the state of California, and I was a courtroom prosecutor before then. And in those roles, I took on perpetrators of all kinds. (CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: Predators who abused women, fraudsters, who ripped off consumers, cheaters who broke the rules for their own gain.(SHOUTING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: So hear me when I say, I know Donald Trump's type.(CHEERING) (APPLAUSE) (CHANTING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: And in this campaign, I promised you, I will proudly put my record against his any day of the week.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: As attorney general of California, I took on one of our country's largest for-profit colleges that was scamming students. Donald Trump ran a for-profit college that scammed students.(BOOING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: As a prosecutor, I specialized in cases involving sexual abuse. Well, Trump was found liable for committing sexual abuse.(BOOING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: As attorney general of California, I took on the big Wall Street banks and held them accountable for fraud.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: Donald Trump was just found guilty of fraud on 34 counts.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: But let's also make no mistake. This campaign is not just about us versus Donald Trump. This campaign is about who we fight for.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: This is about who we fight for.Just look at how we are running our campaigns. So Donald Trump is relying on support from billionaires and big corporations and he is trading access in exchange for campaign contributions. (BOOING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: A couple of months ago, you all saw that a couple of months ago at Mar-a-Lago, he literally promised big oil companies, big oil lobbyists he would do their bidding for $1 billion in campaign donations.(BOOING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: On the other hand, we are running a people-power campaign.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: And because we are a people-powered campaign, that is how you know we will be a people-first presidency.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: And, Wisconsin, this campaign is also about two different visions for our nation. One, where we are focused on the future. The other focused on the past.We believe in a future where every person has the opportunity, not just to get by, but to get ahead. (CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: A future where no child has to grow up in poverty.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: Where every worker has the freedom to join a union.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: Where every person has an affordable health care --(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: -- affordable child care --(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: -- and paid family leave.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: We believe in a future where every senior can retire with dignity.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: So all of this is to say building up the middleclass will be a defining goal of my presidency.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: Because here's the thing we all hear and Wisconsin knows. When our middle-classes is strong, America is strong.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: But Donald Trump wants to take our country backward. He and his extreme Project 2025 agenda --(BOOING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: -- will weaken the middle-class. Like we know we've got to take this serious. I can't believe they put that in writing.(LAUGHTER)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: Read it. It's 900 pages.But here's the thing. You -- when you read it, you will see that Donald Trump intends to cut Social Security and Medicare. (BOOING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: He intends to give tax breaks to billionaires and big corporations and make working families foot the bill.(BOOING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: They intend to end the Affordable Care Act.(BOOING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: And take us back then to a time when insurance companies had the power to deny people with pre-existing conditions.(BOOING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: Remember what that was like? Children with asthma, women who survived breast cancer, grandparents with diabetes. America has tried these failed economic policies before. But we are not going back.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: We are not going back.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: We are not going back.(CHEERING) (CHANTING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: I'll tell you why we're not going back. Because ours is a fight for the future.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: And it is a fight for freedom.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: Generations of Americans -- generations. And we have to remember this. The shoulders on which we stand, generations of Americans before us, led the fight for freedom.And now, Wisconsin, the baton is in our hands. (CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: We, who believe in the sacred freedom to vote, will make sure every American has the ability to cast their ballot and have it counted.(CHEERING) (APPLAUSE)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: We, who believe that every person in our nation should -- who should have the freedom to live safe from the terror of gun violence.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: And we, who believe in reproductive freedom --(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: -- will stop Donald Trump's extreme abortion bans because we trust women to make decisions about their own their own bodies.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: And not let big government tell them what to do.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: When Congress passes a law to restore reproductive freedoms, as president of the United States, I will sign it into law.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: So, Wisconsin, ultimately, in this election, we each face a question(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: And to your point, do we want to live in a country of freedom, compassion and rule of law --(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: -- or a country of chaos, fear and hate? (CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: And here's the beauty of this moment. We each have the power to answer that question. The power is with the people.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: We each have the power to answer that question. And in the next 105 days, then we have work to do.(SHOUTING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: We have doors to knock on, we have phone calls to make, we have voters to register.(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: And we have an election to win!(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: So, Wisconsin, today I ask you, are you ready to get to work?(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: Do we believe in freedom?(SHOUTING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: Do we believe in opportunity?(SHOUTING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: Do we believe in the promise of America?(SHOUTING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: And are we ready to fight for it?(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: And when we fight, we win!(CHEERING)

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: God bless you. Glod bless --(CHEERING) (SINGING)

utterances.speaker: KEILAR
utterances.sentences: And there it is, that Beyonce song to wrap it up, which ties obviously in with a message that she is putting forth there, a country about freedom, not about chaos.I want to bring in Jeff Zeleny and Kristen Hollmes to talk a little bit about what we're seeing. I mean, the thing that strikes me, Jeff, is just the contrast of a Vice President Harris to a President Biden on the campaign trail.

utterances.speaker: JEFF ZELENY, CNN CHIEF NATIONAL AFFAIRS CORRESPONDENT
utterances.sentences: Without question. With the same set of facts, the same opponent, but delivered in a, I mean, remarkably -- choose your word -- different way.I mean, this is a prosecutor making her case. This is also the same vice president who has been out there really for the last three years making speeches, but not when she is at the top of the ticket. Something has changed obviously. Now this is her burden. This is her case. And often, when the vice president has been out there -- I've been at several of her rallies -- she's been talking about the Affordable Care Act, the infrastructure fund. She's been selling the administration's programs, but not in a political speech like this. So look, the race to define Vice President Kamala Harris is on. She is locked in this race. Obviously, she's trying to define herself as a prosecutor. And the Republicans are also trying to define her. But in this key moment here, right out of the gate, it was just striking to watch. I mean, she said it's 105 days to Election Day. Yes. We have work to do. We have an election to win. She's not saying that she has this. But Democrats just feel a breath of fresh air, a chance that they can actually be competitive in this race. But just judging her stamina, her energy and her acuity at taking the --- on Donald Trump. We're in an entirely different race now.
